[normal] UK solution for cyclists approaching a roundabout (
[normal]Googe
[normal] 
[normal]Streetview
[normal] reference) Use your mouse to rotate it a bit if necessary.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]http://goo.gl/maps/hkI4W
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The (unacceptably narrow) cycle line just stops. And here's a Dutch one
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]http://goo.gl/maps/njla5
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]An
[normal]d a Danish one (though roundabouts are rare)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]http://goo.gl/maps/XK7Hc
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]And a German one (roundabouts rare again)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]http://goo.gl/maps/64cv8
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]And a French one
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]http://goo.gl/maps/DKJlE
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Dutch start where the UK ends and the rest continue where the UK 
[normal]one ends.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Footnote: Roger Geffen often says that you 
[normal]cant
[normal] simply copy Dutch infrastructure and expect it to work. Why not? Has it been tried?  I'm not sure it has, particularly the 
[normal]priortisation
[normal] of pedestrians and cyclists at junctions. This sounds like a
[normal]n unsupported assertion to me. Why not German, Danish or French as above? If there had been full Dutch-style intervention at Bow roundabout, I would assert that none of the deaths would have occurred. 
[normal]------------
[normal]On HGV prohibition - 
[normal]the real reason you 
[normal]ban HGVs at peak times is to make life pleasanter for everyone else. The 
[normal]pedestrianised
[normal] area of Kingston upon Thames is a good example. 
[normal]On the risk to cyclists issue 
[normal]-  there
[normal] is one cycling HGV driver who regularly posts on cycling forums and he says visib
[normal]ility is not really an issue (unless like one recent high profile case the driver's eyesight is defective), attention is. What is disgraceful in the London deaths is that these trucks are being driven by people who must be seeing hundreds of cyclists a day
[normal] and should be used to their behaviour, yet they are still are either not paying enough attention or trying to bully their way through. They are the 
[normal]professionals,
[normal] cyclists (and pedestrians and ordinary motorists) are the amateurs. The haulage associations
[normal] and police should be sorting this out. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]I think if you asked an HGV driver (and possibly most motorists), would they like cyclists to be kept away from them (by segregation and traffic light phasing), they would be in favour. But go ahead - ask them this
[normal] question. The FTA recently decried any suggestion of a ban, but failed to come up with any alternatives.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Thank you
